abstract: >-
  Prompt as a Process (PaaP) is a framework for treating Markdown SOPs as
  deployable applications, runnable end-to-end by sufficiently reliable
  language models. v0.3 (2026-04-26) tests whether the framework holds up
  at output time. The repository formalizes the framework via 25
  architectural principles with archetype-aware applicability, a scoring
  rubric, an evaluation instrument (`/paap-eval`), and a generator
  (`meta-paap v2.0`) that produces SKILL.md files following the rubric
  with explicit Iron Law + Rationalizations to Reject patterns plus a
  closed self-observation loop. Empirical layer: an N=80 community-skill
  survey across 36 distinct authors; a 5-rater multi-model kappa pilot
  spanning 3 Claude personas + GPT-5.4 (via Codex CLI) + Gemini-3-pro-
  preview (via Gemini CLI), with mean GPT-5.4 ↔ Claude-pragmatic
  grade-step distance 1.20 vs Gemini-3 ↔ Claude-pragmatic 2.30; a
  5-workflow × 3-input × 3-judge output-quality experiment (45
  judgments) showing handwritten edge on voice-shaped workflows and
  generated edge on rubric-articulable ones; a 4-workflow × 3-input ×
  3-judge community-skill head-to-head (36 judgments) where meta-paap
  v2 wins 29/36 against community-authored skills, with the
  `obra/test-driven-development` case (5/9 community) marking the
  production-iteration moat; and a 0/36 provenance-prediction pattern
  showing blind judges systematically mis-attribute generated outputs
  as hand-authored. Intended for practitioners authoring or evaluating
  LLM workflow files, and researchers studying the post-orchestration-
  framework ecosystem. The v0.3 thesis: PaaP captures form quickly
  through articulable process; production iteration deepens substance
  the rubric cannot describe.
